    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘No Other Choice’",
      "note": "Park Chan-wook",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "No Other Choice",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Park Chan-wook's adaptation of Donald Westlake's novel The Axe (co-written with Lee Kyoung-mi, Don McKellar, and Lee Ja-hye), getting a wider release in January. A laid-off paper-company man, played by Lee Byung-hun in a near-slapstick register, starts bumbling his way through killing off his rivals for the few remaining jobs. Sean's favorite of the year: a sustained Hitchcockian comedy-thriller with a Coen-brothers everyone's-a-moron streak and ornate technique. It ends on a chilling stock-footage sequence of robots felling trees, the AI competitor the hero can never beat."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "In conversation",
      "guest": "Park Chan-wook on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "No Other Choice",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Park (through interpreter Jiwon Lee) on moving the American-set novel to Korea, the bonsai motif his production designer sparked, the arduous hunt for the cookie-cutter 'French-style' house, chasing a film look on digital, and the oven-mitt-and-Santa-glove kill. He ends on Nabokov's Pale Fire as his last great read."
        }
      ]
    }
